@mivanac I know this is draft but I think some input could guide. Perhaps so we can distinguish any arbitrary int[] from a bucket set maybe BucketSet should encapsulate this int[]? Is the rational for just int[] to save the extra allocation of the BucketSet object? If so maybe a set of static methods on a BucketSet helper class to encapsulate some of the logic, like length, iteration, set operations, such that no operations are done directly on the int[] but only through the helper. 
```
class BucketSet {
static int get(int[] bucketSet, int index) {
   return bucketSet[I+1];
}

static int length(int[] bucketSet) {
  return null == bucketSet || bucketSet.length < 2 ? 0 : bucketSet[0];
}

}

The `OutOfMemoryError` doesn't have anything to do with the changes introduced through this `PR`, it's caused by the fact that all classes inheriting from `WANTestBase` have `off-heap` [enabled by default](https://github.com/apache/geode/blob/develop/geode-wan/src/distributedTest/java/org/apache/geode/internal/cache/wan/WANTestBase.java#L3851-L3861):

```
  @Override
  public Properties getDistributedSystemProperties() {
    // For now all WANTestBase tests allocate off-heap memory even though
    // many of them never use it.
    // The problem is that WANTestBase has static methods that create instances
    // of WANTestBase (instead of instances of the subclass). So we can't override
    // this method so that only the off-heap subclasses allocate off heap memory.
    Properties props = new Properties();
    props.setProperty(OFF_HEAP_MEMORY_SIZE, "300m");
    return props;
  }
```

Since this `PR` modifies some tests in `geode-wan`, the `StressNewTest` job is kicking in and executing all those tests multiple times, thus causing the OOME. See [GEODE-7163](https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/GEODE-7163).

@alb3rtobr You're right about the behavior. My apologies for not reading my own JIRA ticket closely before commenting. Your choice of words (and singular verb) is correct as written.
Perhaps as a concession to inattentive readers like myself, may I request that you say "Action to be taken on all of the entries..." ? Just a suggestion - not a requirement.
Thanks for fixing this bug in the docs.
